{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Bu4H3kWTQpAYgJy515zYt8","type":"tool_result","content":"  1270→// projectLabels builds a mapping from full project directory paths to short\n  1271→// display labels. Each label is the final directory component (e.g.\n  1272→// \"myproject\" from \"/home/user/workspace/myproject\"). When two projects share\n  1273→// the same final name, the parent directory is prepended to disambiguate\n  1274→// (e.g. \"foo/bar\" vs \"baz/bar\").\n  1275→func projectLabels(dirs []string) map[string]string {\n  1276→\tlabels := make(map[string]string, len(dirs))\n  1277→\t// Group dirs by their base name to detect conflicts.\n  1278→\tbyBase := map[string][]string{}\n  1279→\tfor _, d := range dirs {\n  1280→\t\tbase := filepath.Base(d)\n  1281→\t\tbyBase[base] = append(byBase[base], d)\n  1282→\t}\n  1283→\tfor base, paths := range byBase {\n  1284→\t\tif len(paths) == 1 {\n  1285→\t\t\tlabels[paths[0]] = base\n  1286→\t\t} else {\n  1287→\t\t\tfor _, p := range paths {\n  1288→\t\t\t\tparent := filepath.Base(filepath.Dir(p))\n  1289→\t\t\t\tlabels[p] = parent + \"/\" + base\n  1290→\t\t\t}\n  1291→\t\t}\n  1292→\t}\n  1293→\treturn labels\n  1294→}\n  1295→\n  1296→type projectEntry struct {\n  1297→\tDir            string\n  1298→\tLabel          string\n  1299→\tContainerCount int"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aced3543-5ed5-4523-b8de-7b978353a1a0","uuid":"cf3d8d5f-28d2-48b9-ba7b-2546bd0a94ec","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go","content":"// projectLabels builds a mapping from full project directory paths to short\n// display labels. Each label is the final directory component (e.g.\n// \"myproject\" from \"/home/user/workspace/myproject\"). When two projects share\n// the same final name, the parent directory is prepended to disambiguate\n// (e.g. \"foo/bar\" vs \"baz/bar\").\nfunc projectLabels(dirs []string) map[string]string {\n\tlabels := make(map[string]string, len(dirs))\n\t// Group dirs by their base name to detect conflicts.\n\tbyBase := map[string][]string{}\n\tfor _, d := range dirs {\n\t\tbase := filepath.Base(d)\n\t\tbyBase[base] = append(byBase[base], d)\n\t}\n\tfor base, paths := range byBase {\n\t\tif len(paths) == 1 {\n\t\t\tlabels[paths[0]] = base\n\t\t} else {\n\t\t\tfor _, p := range paths {\n\t\t\t\tparent := filepath.Base(filepath.Dir(p))\n\t\t\t\tlabels[p] = parent + \"/\" + base\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn labels\n}\n\ntype projectEntry struct {\n\tDir            string\n\tLabel          string\n\tContainerCount int","numLines":30,"startLine":1270,"totalLines":1301}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JreVCrAkntd6GyZesKvVrd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Here's my plan:\n\n1. **Add route** `GET /projects/{name}/runs` in handler.go that points to `handleRunsList`\n2. **Update `handleRunsList`** to check for path value `name` first (resolve label → dir), then fall back to query param `project`\n3. **Update templates** to use `/projects/{{label}}/runs` instead of `/runs?project={{dir}}`\n\nLet me also need to pass the project label to the runs template so the JS can construct the right URL.\n\nWait, the runs page filter dropdown needs to redirect to `/projects/{label}/runs` when a project is selected and `/runs` when \"all projects\" is selected. \n\nI need to update the `filterByProject` function in the JS to handle this routing. The tricky part is that `handleRunsList` currently passes `ProjectFilter` as the directory, but I need to also pass the label so the template can build the correct URLs. I could either pass both values or restructure how I'm handling the project data. The key insight is that the runs list serves two purposes: showing all runs at `/runs` and showing project-specific runs at `/projects/<label>/runs`, so the filter dropdown needs to know which URL to redirect to based on the selection. a specific project (new)\n\nFor the handler, when hitting `/projects/{name}/runs`, I resolve the label to a dir using `resolveProjectDir`, then use that dir to filter. But `resolveProjectDir` writes a JSON error, which isn't great for an HTML page. Let me handle it differently - or I could create a similar resolver that writes HTML errors.\n\nActually, let me keep it simple. I'll modify `handleRunsList` to check if there's a `name` path value, and if so, use `resolveProjectDir` logic (but return an HTML error instead). Then update the route registration and templates.\n\nWait, but `resolveProjectDir` uses `r.PathValue(\"name\")`. If I register `/projects/{name}/runs`, then both this route and `/projects/{name}` use `{name}`, so `resolveProjectDir` would work.\n\nThe real issue is that `resolveProjectDir` returns JSON errors, so I'll inline the resolution logic directly in `handleRunsList` to return HTML errors instead. My approach: add the new route, then in the handler check for the path parameter first, resolve the project directory using the label lookup, and fall back to the query parameter for backward compatibility—or better yet, redirect old query-based requests to the new URL structure. Now I need to update the template links across the board—switching from the query parameter approach to the new URL pattern with the project label in the path. The JavaScript filter function will also need to construct URLs using the label instead of the directory, so I'll need to pass that data through to the template context. I need to change it to use label and go to `/projects/<label>/runs`.\n\nThe dropdown options currently have `value=\"{{.Dir}}\"`. I should change them to `value=\"{{.Label}}\"` and update the JS accordingly.\n\nWait, but the polling JS also uses `currentProject` with the dir to call `/api/runs?project=<dir>`. If I change the dropdown value to label, I need to update the API call too... or keep both values.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach: have the dropdown value be the label, and use a data attribute for the dir. Then the JS redirect uses label, and the API polling uses dir.\n\nHmm, that's getting complex. Let me simplify:\n\n1. The dropdown `filterByProject` function redirects the browser to `/projects/{label}/runs` \n2. The template data for the runs page should include the `ProjectLabel` (label of the filtered project, if any)\n3. The polling JS needs `currentProject` (dir) for the API call - this can come from a template variable\n\nLooking at the template data, the handler passes the project filter as dir and a map of labels. The JS currently gets the dir as